        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="crossref-entry">
      <h3><a href="/posts/17-examples-outperform-instructions/">#17. Examples Outperform Instructions</a></h3>
      <div class="crossref-connections">
        <div class="crossref-connection crossref-connection--whoop">
          <span class="crossref-badge crossref-badge--whoop">WHOOP</span>
          <p>The evaluation framework uses synthetic "Personas" — reproducible member profiles with specific data characteristics. These are structured examples that test whether the agent responds correctly to concrete scenarios, not abstract instructions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="crossref-entry">
      <h3><a href="/posts/19-system-prompts-are-contracts/">#19. System Prompts Are Contracts</a></h3>
      <div class="crossref-connections">
        <div class="crossref-connection crossref-connection--cursor">
          <span class="crossref-badge crossref-badge--cursor">Cursor</span>
          <p>Priompt makes system prompts literally contractual. Each element has a priority score, and when the token budget is exceeded, lower-priority elements are dropped deterministically. The prompt is a structured allocation of context with enforced constraints.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="crossref-connection crossref-connection--whoop">
          <span class="crossref-badge crossref-badge--whoop">WHOOP</span>
          <p>Inline tools embed data retrieval directly in the system prompt via markup language. The prompt specifies <code>{% raw %}{{@tool1}}{% endraw %}</code> and the data is injected before generation begins. The system prompt is a contract that guarantees what data the model will have.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="crossref-deeper">Go deeper: <a href="/articles/advanced-prompt-engineering/">Advanced Prompt Engineering: Beyond the Basics</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="crossref-entry">
      <h3><a href="/posts/22-chain-of-thought-is-a-debugging-tool-not-just-a-performance-trick/">#22. Chain of Thought Is a Debugging Tool, Not Just a Performance Trick</a></h3>
      <div class="crossref-connections">
        <div class="crossref-connection crossref-connection--cursor">
          <span class="crossref-badge crossref-badge--cursor">Cursor</span>
          <p>When Cursor evaluated GPT-5, the <code>minimal</code> reasoning mode actually underperformed GPT-4.1 for chat. Different reasoning depths suit different tasks — chain of thought helps complex reasoning but hurts low-latency chat.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="crossref-entry">
      <h3><a href="/posts/25-learn-to-recognize-hallucination-patterns-in-your-domain/">#25. Learn to Recognize Hallucination Patterns in Your Domain</a></h3>
      <div class="crossref-connections">
        <div class="crossref-connection crossref-connection--whoop">
          <span class="crossref-badge crossref-badge--whoop">WHOOP</span>
          <p>The "Data Driven" metric measures how often responses incorporate actual individualized data rather than generic advice. When they migrated to GPT-5.1, this metric jumped from 42.6% to 56.6% — the old model was hallucinating generic health advice over half the time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

